File: e2e/npm-discovery.e2e.ts.

Multiple tests in this file create temp directories with fake npm packages (e.g., lines ~50-80 in the first test). The pattern is:

```
const npmGlobalDir = fs.mkdtempSync(...);
// ... create fake packages ...
const server = await startMcpServer(configDir, true, undefined, { OPENTABS_NPM_GLOBAL_DIR: npmGlobalDir });
try {
  // test body
} finally {
  await server.kill();
  cleanupTestConfigDir(configDir);
  fs.rmSync(npmGlobalDir, ...);
}
```

If `startMcpServer` rejects (before `server` is assigned), the `finally` block tries to call `server.kill()` which throws because `server` is undefined, and the subsequent cleanup lines (including `fs.rmSync(npmGlobalDir, ...)`) never execute.

The fix should restructure the try/finally to ensure temp dirs are always cleaned up. Use `let server: McpServer | undefined` and guard `server?.kill()` in the finally block, or nest the try blocks so temp dir cleanup is in an outer finally.

File: e2e/browser-tools.e2e.ts, approximately lines 95-120 (the waitForExecFileCleanup helper function).

The current code:
```
const waitForExecFileCleanup = async (adaptersDir: string, ...) => {
  const deadline = Date.now() + timeoutMs;
  while (Date.now() < deadline) {
    try {
      const files = fs.readdirSync(adaptersDir).filter(f => f.startsWith('__exec-'));
      if (files.length === 0) return;
    } catch {
      // directory may not exist — continue polling
    }
    await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, intervalMs));
  }
  throw new Error(...);
};
```

The catch block swallows the ENOENT error and continues the loop, causing a timeout. Instead, the catch block should check if the error code is ENOENT and return immediately (no directory = no leftover files = clean). Other errors (permission denied, etc.) should continue polling or re-throw.
